# Git commits

## Enforcement (strict)

- This rule is **mandatory** for all agent-authored git actions in this repository.
- If a git command would violate any section below, **do not run it**. Stop, explain the exact rule conflict, and ask for explicit user confirmation or clarification.
- When multiple instructions exist, prefer the **most restrictive** interpretation that keeps history safe and intentional.

## When commits are allowed

- **Create a git commit only when the user explicitly asks** (e.g. “commit this”, “make a commit”, “git commit”). Phrases like “save my work” or “checkpoint” count as explicit only if they clearly mean a **git commit**—when in doubt, **ask** before committing.
- **Do not commit** to “helpfully” save progress, to finish a task, or because a change set “feels done.” **Never** run `git commit` without a clear, direct request to commit.
- **Do not** amend, rebase, or otherwise rewrite history unless the user explicitly asks.

## Push and branches

- **Do not** `git push` (or force-push) unless the user **explicitly** asks to push.
- **Do not** merge or rebase branches unless the user **explicitly** asks (same spirit as commits).

### Branch model (this project)

| Branch | Role |
|--------|------|
| **`master`** | **Default integration and release line.** Production-ready history; receives merged feature work via pull request (or explicit user-directed merge). |
| **`feat/<name>`** or **`feature/<name>`** | **Feature development.** Branch from up-to-date **`master`**, implement, then open a PR into **`master`** when ready. |

**Intended flow:** `feat/...` (or `feature/...`) → **`master`** via **pull request** on the host (GitHub, etc.). This repo does **not** use a separate long-lived `dev` branch.

**Agent defaults when the user asks for a new branch:** create **`feat/<short-descriptive-slug>`** from **`master`** (after `git fetch` / `checkout master` / `pull` when using a remote), unless the user names another pattern (e.g. `fix/...`, `chore/...`).

**Release / merge to `master`:** Prefer completing a **PR** on the remote. Do **not** recommend `git checkout master && git merge feat/...` as the normal path without the user asking. A **local** merge is acceptable only when the user **explicitly** asks and confirms compatibility (build/tests as they care about).

**Hosting note:** Enable branch protection on **`master`** (require PR, reviews, status checks) when using GitHub/GitLab so merges go through review.

## Staging scope

- **Stage only** paths the user named, or changes that clearly belong to the requested commit. If the working tree has **other** modified or untracked files, **list them** and either leave them unstaged or **ask** whether to include them—**do not** silently `git add -A` unless the user explicitly asked to commit **everything**.
- Before committing, prefer **`git status`** (or equivalent) so staged vs unstaged is intentional.

## One logical change per commit

- Prefer **one coherent story** per commit. If the working tree mixes unrelated changes (e.g. a **BUGFIX** and a **DOCS** refresh with no link), **tell the user** and offer **split commits** (stage subsets with separate messages) or **ask** which single prefix and scope they want for this commit.

## Safety (never commit)

- **Secrets:** Do not commit API keys, passwords, tokens, private keys, or full `.env` files that hold secrets. If such material appears staged or in diffs, **stop**, warn the user, and remove it from the index before proceeding.
- **Generated and ignored artifacts:** Do not add paths listed in `.gitignore` (e.g. `target/`, `data/`, `*.db`, coverage output) unless the user **explicitly** asks to track that path anyway.

## Hooks

- **Do not** bypass Git hooks with `--no-verify` / `-n` unless the user **explicitly** asks to skip hooks for that commit.

